Monte-Carlo Introduction

There are two flavors of MC algorithms: Direct Sampling MC and Markov Chain MC.

Let us illustrate both on the simple example of the 'pebble' game - calculating the value of by sampling interior of a circle.

1. Direct-Sampling by Rejection [pebble game]

Main feature of the DS MC - memorylessness - new sample is chosen completely independently from the previous one.

In [1]:
using PyPlot

N=100000                             # number of dots/samples

x_in = Float64[]
y_in = Float64[]
x_out = Float64[]
y_out = Float64[]

count = 0

for i in 1:N
    x = rand()
    y = rand()                       # generate samples uniformly dstributed within a square
    if (x-0.5)^2+(y-0.5)^2 < 0.25    # accept if the sample within the sphere
        count = count + 1
        push!(x_in, x)
        push!(y_in, y)
        else                         # reject otherwise
        push!(x_out, x)
        push!(y_out, y)        
    end    
end

scatter(x_in, y_in, s=10)
scatter(x_out, y_out, s=10,alpha = 0.01)

pi = 4*count/N                      # estimation for \pi
Out[1]:
3.1396

2. MCMC [pebble game]

MCMC keeps the memory - the next sample is chosen based on the current sample.

In [2]:
using Distributions
using PyPlot

N=100000                                # number of steps/samples
delta = 1                               # parameter related to the step size

x=1.0 # Initial coordinates
y=1.0

count = 0

d = Uniform(-delta,delta)

x_in = Float64[]                        # preparing data for the scatter plot
y_in = Float64[]
x_out = Float64[]
y_out = Float64[]

for i in 1:N
    
    dx = rand(d,1)
    dy = rand(d,1)
    x = x + dx[1]
    y = y + dy[1]
    
                                        # periodic boundary conditions for the walker 
    if x>1
        x = x-2
    end
    if x<-1
        x = x+2
    end   
    if y>1
        y = y-2
    end
    if y<-1
        y = y+2
    end
    
    if x^2 + y^2 < 1
        count = count + 1
        push!(x_in, x)
        push!(y_in, y)
    else
        push!(x_out, x)
        push!(y_out, y)  
    end
end

scatter(x_in, y_in, s=10, )
scatter(x_out, y_out, s=10, alpha=0.01)

pi = 4*count/N
Out[2]:
3.15008

Monte-Carlo Direct Sampling

1. Direct Sampling by Mapping

The function rand() generates the random variable xx, uniformly distributed at [0,1)[0,1) interval, xU([0,1))xU([0,1)). Our goal is to utilize random xx to generate random yy distributed exponentially within [0,)[0,), yexp(y)yexp(y).

One simple way to achive the goal is to relate the two variables (map xx to yy) through explicit formula: exp(y)=xexp(y)=x. (Indeed, exp(y)dy=dxexp(y)dy=dx.)

In [3]:
using PyPlot
N=10000
x = rand(N)
y = -log(x)
PyPlot.plt[:hist](y, bins = 25, range=(0,10), normed=1)
PyPlot.title("Exponential Random Variable")
Out[3]:
PyObject <matplotlib.text.Text object at 0x00000000226DC9B0>

Another example of DS MS by mapping, Box Muller Algotithm, which is a smart way to map two-dimensional random variable distributed uniformly within a box to the two-dimensional Gaussian (normal) random variable:

dxdy2e(x2+y2)/2=20d20rdrer2/2=20d20dzez=10d10d=1.dxdy2e(x2+y2)/2=02d20rdrer2/2=02d20dzez=01d01d=1.

Thus, the deisred mapping is (,)(x,y)(,)(x,y), where x=2logcos(2)x=2logcos(2) and y=2logsin(2)y=2logsin(2).

2. Direct Sampling by Rejection (second time)

Let us now show how to get positive Gaussian (normal) random variable from an exponential random variable through rejection.

  • First, one samples from the exponential distribution: x0(x)={ex0x>0,otherwisex0(x)={exx>0,0otherwise

  • Second, aiming to get a sample from the positive half of Gaussian, x0(x)={2/exp(x2/2)0x>0,otherwisex0(x)={2/exp(x2/2)x>0,0otherwise, one accepts the generated sample with the probability

    p(x)=1M2/exp(xx2/2)p(x)=1M2/exp(xx2/2)
    where MM is a constant which should be larger than, max((x)/0(x))=2/e1/21.32max((x)/0(x))=2/e1/21.32, to guarantee that p(x)1p(x)1 for all x>0x>0.

In [12]:
using PyPlot
using Distributions

function rho_0_pdf(x) # initial=exponential distribution
    return exp(-x) 
end

function rho_pdf(x) # desired=Gaussian distribution
    return (2/sqrt(2*pi))*exp(-x^2/2) 
end

rho0 = Exponential() # initial distribution
M = 1.5            # parameter M 
N = 10000
i = 1
reject=0
rand_var = Float64[] # Generated Random Variable

while i<N
    sample = rand(rho0, 1)
    unif = rand()
    if unif[1] < rho_pdf(sample[1])/(rho_0_pdf(sample[1])*M)
        push!(rand_var, sample[1])
        i=i+1
    else
        reject=reject+1
    end   
end

epsilon_values = rand(rho0, N)

PyPlot.plt[:hist](epsilon_values, bins = 100, range=(0,5), normed=1)
PyPlot.plt[:hist](rand_var, bins = 100, range=(0,5), normed=1)
PyPlot.title("Exponential and Gaussian Distributions")

reject=reject/N   # rejection probability
Out[12]:
0.4997

Note that the rejection algorithm has the advantage that it can be applied even when the probability densities are known only upto a multiplicative constant. (We will discuss issues related to this constant, also called in the multivariate case the partition function, a number of times later in the course.)

3. Importance Sampling

As we saw MC is useful for computing sums/integrals/expectations. Suppose we want to compute an expectation of a function, f(x)f(x), over the distribution, (x)(x), i.e. dx(x)f(x)dx(x)f(x), in the regime where f(x)f(x) and 0(x)0(x) are concentrated around very different xx. In this case overlap of ff and 0(x)0(x) is small and as a result a lot of MC samples will be 'wasted'.

Importance Sampling is the method which helps to fix the small-overlap problem. It is based on adjusting the distribution function from (x)(x) to 0(x)0(x) and then utilizing the following obvious formula

E[f(x)]=dx(x)f(x)=dx0(x)f(x)(x)0(x)=E0[f(x)(x)0(x)]E[f(x)]=dx(x)f(x)=dx0(x)f(x)(x)0(x)=E0[f(x)(x)0(x)]

Consider an illustrative DS example, (x)=12exp(x22)(x)=12exp(x22) and f(x)=exp((x4)22)f(x)=exp((x4)22), vs IS with the proposal distribution, 0(x)=1exp((x2)2)0(x)=1exp((x2)2).

In [56]:
using PyPlot

N=50
x=randn(N)
xp=x/sqrt(2)+2

f=exp(-0.5(x-4).^2)
fp=exp(-0.5(xp-4).^2-0.5xp.^2+(xp-2).^2)/sqrt(2)

x0=linspace(-3,8,100)
f0=exp(-0.5(x0-4).^2)
fp0=exp(-0.5(x0-4).^2-0.5x0.^2+(x0-2).^2)/sqrt(2)
rho=exp(-x0.^2/2)/sqrt(2pi)
rho0=exp(-(x0-2).^2)/sqrt(pi)
plot(x0, f0, color="red", linewidth=2.0, linestyle="--")
plot(x0, rho, color="red", linewidth=2.0, linestyle="-")
plot(x0, fp0, color="green", linewidth=2.0, linestyle="--")
plot(x0, rho0, color="green", linewidth=2.0, linestyle="-")
plot(x,0.1ones(N),"ro")
plot(xp,0.3ones(N),"go")

(sum(f)/N,sum(fp)/N)
Out[56]:
(0.00400554840012989,0.012951112459987979)

We are clearly wasting samples with DS.

Note one big problem with IS. In the real (multi-dimensional) cases we typically do not have a good guess for 0(x)0(x). One way of solving this problem is to search for good 0(x)0(x) adaptively. A sophisticated adaptive importance sampling package is available at https://pypi.python.org/pypi/pypmc/1.0.
